===Etymology 4===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|と}}

{{IPAfont|⟨to<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → {{IPAchar|/*tə/}} → {{IPAchar|/to/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=と|-}}, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|sort=と|*tə}}.  Appears mainly as an affixing element indicating place, as in {{m|ja|後||tr=ato|after; behind; the back of something}}, from {{m|ja|跡||tr=ato|footprint, track}}, itself a compound of {{m|ja|足||tr=a|foot}} + {{m|ja|所||tr=to|place}}; or in {{m|ja|留まる||tr=todomaru|to stop in a place}}.

In modern Japanese references,<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref> there are various compound terms ending in ''-to'' or ''-do'' that are spelled and / or described as deriving from this {{m|ja|所||tr=to|place}}, including {{m|ja|隈所||tr=kumato|a bent and twisted place, such as a tunnel, out of sight}}, {{m|ja|立ち所||tr=tachido|standing place}}, {{m|ja|竈||tr=kamado|kiln}}.  However, a historical analysis reveals that many of these terms do not derive from {{m|ja|所}}, {{m|ja|処}} {{IPAfont|⟨to<sub>2</sub>⟩}} “place”, but rather from {{m|ja|戸}}, {{m|ja|門}} {{IPAfont|⟨to<sub>1</sub>⟩}} “gate, door, place of entry and exit”.

